    "narrative": "For today\u2019s slate, **Jos\u00e9 Ram\u00edrez** (71.71) and **Jonathan Aranda** (70.47) represent our elite tier of starts, offering the most secure paths to production. **Jos\u00e9 Ram\u00edrez** benefits from a high base floor and a favorable matchup against Cameron, with his projected output largely immune to the slight wind-in disadvantage. Meanwhile, **Jonathan Aranda** is a standout play due to a high-leverage spot in the batting order against Javier Assad; his 19% SP skill advantage and strong 0.382 xwOBA highlight his potential to drive R and RBI totals. **Yainer Diaz** (63.74) also warrants attention as a strong start against Freeland; despite the uncertainty of his #8 lineup slot, his base projection is bolstered by an elite park factor and a favorable platoon matchup.\n\nThe decision to bench **Geraldo Perdomo** (43.42) was the most difficult call of the morning. While **Geraldo Perdomo** carries high-floor value, his upside for this specific matchup was suppressed by a poor park factor and a 9% reduction due to wind, causing him to fall just behind the efficiency thresholds of **Jeremiah Jackson** (53.13) and **Masyn Winn** (53.18). We are also exercising caution with **Brendan Donovan** (49.74) and **Cal Raleigh** (47.54), both of whom are facing the formidable Nathan Eovaldi. The 19% negative SP skill adjustment for both players makes them risky starts, but their projected role at the top of the order remains enough to justify their presence in the starting lineup over the deeper bench options like **Matt Chapman** or **Luis Arraez**, who are similarly hindered by the tough Cristopher S\u00e1nchez matchup. \n\nFinally, managers should monitor the \"Lineup Pending\" flags attached to nearly all our starters. Should the final lineups reveal that **Gleyber Torres** or **Brendan Donovan** have been shifted down the order, their daily efficiency scores will drop further, potentially placing them near the \"Below floor\" range. Be particularly wary of **Daulton Varsho** (49.62); while he provides necessary versatility, he is facing the high-strikeout arm of Yoshinobu Yamamoto, and the threat of a stolen base being stifled by an elite hold SP creates a low ceiling for his 5x5 contribution today.",
